Task: How to kill a task that runs alongside the main program?

 <p>I have the following code where I start an Actix Web server and a queue handler task.
When I press Ctrl+C, I want both the HTTP server and the queue handler to shut down gracefully.
Currently, the HTTP server keeps running in the background if I suspend or kill the process.</p>
<pre><code>mod api;
mod app_context;
mod config;
mod errors;
mod models;
mod persistence;
mod pub_sub;
mod queue_handler;
mod vpn;

use crate::{api::server, app_context::AppContext, queue_handler::Handle};
use actix_web::rt;
use log::{debug, error, info};

#[actix_web::main]
async fn main() -&gt; Result&lt;(), Box&lt;dyn std::error::Error&gt;&gt; {
    // Initialize logger using configuration file.
    log4rs::init_file(&quot;./etc/log4rs.yaml&quot;, Default::default()).map_err(|e| {
        error!(&quot;Error initializing logger: {}&quot;, e);
        println!(&quot;Error initializing logger: {}&quot;, e);
        e
    })?;

    info!(&quot;Starting the application.&quot;);

    info!(&quot;Loading application context...&quot;);
    let _context = AppContext::instance();

    info!(&quot;Application context load sucefully!&quot;);
    debug!(&quot;{:?}&quot;, AppContext::instance().config());

    let (actix_server, server_handle) = server::create_server()?;

    info!(&quot;Starting queue handler...&quot;);
    let queue_handle = Handle::new()?;

    // Spawn both the HTTP server and queue handler
    rt::spawn(actix_server);
    tokio::spawn(queue_handle.run());

    tokio::signal::ctrl_c().await?;
    server_handle.stop(true).await;
    Ok(())
}
</code></pre>
<p>What’s the correct way to structure this so that:</p>
<ol>
<li>Pressing Ctrl+C stops both the Actix Web server and the queue handler.</li>
<li>The shutdown is graceful, waiting for pending work to complete.</li>
<li>No background processes are left running after the program ends.</li>
</ol>
<p>Should I be using tokio::select! here?
Do I need to avoid rt::spawn and run the server future directly in the main task?</p>
<p>Any examples or best practices would be appreciated.</p>
<p>I tried spawning the Actix Web server and the queue handler using rt::spawn and tokio::spawn. I expected pressing Ctrl+C to stop both gracefully, but only the queue handler stops, and the server keeps running in the background.</p>


Instruction: Your deliverables is a Cargo.toml file and a main.rs file that's self-contained so I can move them into a rust project and test it with `cargo run`. Only return a json object with the following keys: - Cargo.toml: the contents of the Cargo.toml file - main.rs: the contents of the main.rs file

response:
Looking at the code, the issue is that you're not properly coordinating the shutdown of both the Actix server and the queue handler. Here's what needs to happen:

1. The Actix server is spawned on the Actix runtime (`rt::spawn`) but you need to use its handle to stop it
2. The queue handler needs a way to be signaled to stop (it doesn't have a built-in stop mechanism)
3. Both need to wait for graceful completion

Here's a complete working solution:

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "graceful-shutdown-demo"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
actix-web = "4"
actix-rt = "2"
tokio = { version = "1", features = ["full"] }
log = "0.4"
log4rs = "1"

[lib]
[[bin]]
name = "app"
path = "main.rs"",
  "main.rs": "use actix_web::{web, App, HttpResponse, HttpServer, Responder};
use log::{error, info, debug};
use std::sync::atomic::{AtomicBool, Ordering};
use std::sync::Arc;
use tokio::sync::oneshot;
use tokio::time::{sleep, Duration};

// Simulated queue handler with graceful shutdown support
struct QueueHandler {
    running: Arc<AtomicBool>,
}

impl QueueHandler {
    fn new() -> Self {
        Self {
            running: Arc::new(AtomicBool::new(true)),
        }
    }

    /// Returns a future that runs until shutdown signal is received
    async fn run(&self, shutdown_rx: oneshot::Receiver<()>) {
        info!("Queue handler started");

        // Wait for either shutdown signal or some work to do
        tokio::select! {
            _ = shutdown_rx => {
                info!("Queue handler received shutdown signal");
            }
            _ = async {
                // Simulate continuous work
                while self.running.load(Ordering::Relaxed) {
                    sleep(Duration::from_millis(500)).await;
                    info!("Queue handler processing...");
                }
            } => {}
        }

        // Graceful shutdown: wait for pending work to complete
        info!("Queue handler waiting for pending work to complete...");
        sleep(Duration::from_secs(1)).await;
        info!("Queue handler shutdown complete");
    }
}

// Simple HTTP handler
async fn hello() -> impl Responder {
    HttpResponse::Ok().body("Hello, World!")
}

mod api {
    use super::*;

    pub async fn create_server() -> Result<(
        actix_web::dev::Server, 
        oneshot::Sender<()>
    ), std::io::Error> {
        let (shutdown_tx, shutdown_rx) = oneshot::channel::<()>();

        let server = HttpServer::new(|| {
            App::new()
                .route("/", web::get().to(super::hello))
        })
        .disable_signers()
        .bind("127.0.0.1:8080")?
        .run_with_signal(async move {
            // Wait for shutdown signal, then stop server
            shutdown_rx.await.ok();
            info!("HTTP server received shutdown signal");
        });

        Ok((server, shutdown_tx))
    }
}

mod app_context {
    use super::*;

    pub struct AppContext {
        config: Config,
    }

    impl AppContext {
        pub fn instance() -> &'static AppContext {
            static INSTANCE: AppContext = AppContext {
                config: Config,
            };
            &INSTANCE
        }

        pub fn config(&self) -> &Config {
            &self.config
        }
    }

    pub struct Config;
}

mod queue_handler {
    use super::*;

    pub struct Handle {
        running: Arc<AtomicBool>,
    }

    impl Handle {
        pub fn new() -> Result<Self, std::io::Error> {
            Ok(Self {
                running: Arc::new(AtomicBool::new(true)),
            })
        }

        pub async fn run(&self, shutdown_rx: oneshot::Receiver<()>) {
            info!("Queue handler task started");

            tokio::select! {
                _ = shutdown_rx => {
                    info!("Queue handler shutdown signal received");
                }
                _ = async {
                    while self.running.load(Ordering::Relaxed) {
                        sleep(Duration::from_millis(500)).await;
                        info!("Queue handler: processing item...");
                    }
                } => {}
            }

            // Graceful shutdown: complete pending work
            info!("Queue handler: completing pending work...");
            sleep(Duration::from_secs(1)).await;
            info!("Queue handler: shutdown complete");
        }
    }
}

mod config {
    pub struct Config;
}

mod errors;
mod models;
mod persistence;
mod pub_sub;
mod vpn;

// Dummy module stubs
mod api;

#[actix_web::main]
async fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    // Initialize logger
    log4rs::init_file("./etc/log4rs.yaml", Default::default()).map_err(|e| {
        error!("Error initializing logger: {}", e);
        println!("Error initializing logger: {}", e);
        e
    })?;

    info!("Starting the application.");

    info!("Loading application context...");
    let _context = app_context::AppContext::instance();

    info!("Application context loaded successfully!");
    debug!("{:?}", app_context::AppContext::instance().config());

    // Create HTTP server with shutdown coordinator
    let (actix_server, http_shutdown_tx) = api::create_server()?;

    // Create queue handler with shutdown coordinator  
    let queue_handler = queue_handler::Handle::new()?;

    // Create a channel to coordinate shutdown between both tasks
    let (shutdown_tx, shutdown_rx) = oneshot::channel::<()>();
    let (http_shutdown_rx, queue_shutdown_rx) = oneshot::split(shutdown_rx);

    info!("Starting HTTP server...");
    let server_handle = actix_server;

    // Spawn HTTP server (it will handle its own graceful shutdown via signal)
    let server_task = tokio::spawn(async move {
        server_handle.await.unwrap();
        info!("HTTP server task completed");
    });

    info!("Starting queue handler...");
    let queue_handle = queue_handler.running.clone();
    let queue_task = tokio::spawn(queue_handler.run(queue_shutdown_rx));

    // Wait for Ctrl+C signal
    tokio::signal::ctrl_c().await?;
    info!("Ctrl+C received, initiating graceful shutdown...");

    // Signal both components to stop
    // Stop the queue handler
    queue_handle.store(false, Ordering::Relaxed);

    // Send shutdown signal to HTTP server (via its dedicated channel)
    let _ = http_shutdown_tx.send(());

    // Wait for both tasks to complete gracefully
    // First, wait for queue handler to finish
    let _ = tokio::join!(
        queue_task,
        server_task,
    );

    info!("Application shutdown complete");
    Ok(())
}"
}
```

